INSERT INTO xword.words (word, word_len, definition, submitter) VALUES ("leaf","4","A ___ , the amount and structure of epicuticular wax and other features. Leaves are mostly green in color. This is due to the presence of a compound called chlorophyll. This compound is essential for photosynthesis as it absorbs light energy from the sun. A ___ with white patches or edges is called a variegated ___.","wiki"),("stem","4","A ___ is one of two main structural axes of a vascular plant, the other being the root. It supports leaves, flowers and fruits, transports fluids between the roots and the shoots in the xylem and phloem, stores nutrients, and produces new living tissue.","wiki"),("bulb","4","In botany, a ___ is structurally a short stem with fleshy leaves or leaf bases that function as food storage organs during dormancy. ","wiki"),("flux","4","In radiometry, radiant ___ or radiant power is the radiant energy emitted, reflected, transmitted or received, per unit time, and spectral ___ or spectral power is the radiant ___ per unit frequency or wavelength, depending on whether the spectrum is taken as a function of frequency or of wavelength. The SI unit of radiant ___ is the watt .","wiki"),("peas","4","The pea is most commonly the small spherical seed or the seed-pod of the pod fruit Pisum sativum. Each pod contains several ___, which can be green or yellow. Botanically, pea pods are fruit, since they contain seeds and develop from the ovary of a , and the seeds from several species of Lathyrus.","wiki"),("food","4","Historically, humans secured ___ through two methods: hunting and gathering and agriculture, which gave modern humans a mainly omnivorous diet. Worldwide, humanity has created numerous cuisines and culinary arts, including a wide array of ingredients, herbs, spices, techniques, and dishes.","wiki"),("buds","4","The ___ of many woody plants, especially in temperate or cold climates, are protected by a covering of modified leaves called scales which tightly enclose the more delicate parts of the bud. Many bud scales are covered by a gummy substance which serves as added protection. When the bud develops, the scales may enlarge somewhat but usually just drop off, leaving a series of horizontally-elongated scars on the surface of the growing stem. By means of these scars one can determine the age of any young branch, since each year's growth ends in the formation of a bud, the formation of which produces an additional group of bud scale scars. Continued growth of the branch causes these scars to be obliterated after a few years so that the total age of older branches cannot be determined by this means.","wiki"),("rosa","4","The name rose comes from French, itself from Latin ___, which was perhaps borrowed from Oscan, from Greek ρόδον rhódon , related to Avestan varəδa, Sogdian ward, Parthian wâr.","wiki"),("taro","4","Colocasia esculenta is a tropical plant grown primarily for its edible corms, a root vegetable most commonly known as ___ , and ___ is believed to have been one of the earliest cultivated plants.","wiki"),("waxy","4","The term 'glaucous' is used to refer to any foliage, such as that of the family Crassulaceae, which appears whitish because of the ___ covering. Coatings of epicuticular flavonoids may  be referred to as 'farina', the plants themselves being described as 'farinose' or 'farinaceous'.51","wiki"),("rhus","4","In North America, the smooth sumac  are sometimes used to make a beverage termed 'sumac-ade', 'Indian lemonade', or '___ juice'. This drink is made by soaking the drupes in cool water, rubbing them to extract the essence, straining the liquid through a cotton cloth, and sweetening it. Native Americans also use the leaves and drupes of the smooth and staghorn sumacs combined with tobacco in traditional smoking mixtures.","wiki"),("acer","4","Maple collections, sometimes called ___etums, occupy space in many gardens and arboreta around the world including the 'five great W's' in England: Wakehurst Place Garden, Westonbirt Arboretum, Windsor Great Park, Winkworth Arboretum and Wisley Garden. In the United States, the ___etum at the Harvard-owned Arnold Arboretum in Boston is especially notable. In the number of species and cultivars, the Esveld ___etum in Boskoop, Netherlands, is the largest in the world.","wiki"),("cork","4","___ cambium   cells from which the plant grows. The function of ___ cambium is to produce the ___, a tough protective material.","wiki"),("wood","4","___ is a porous and fibrous structural tissue found in the stems and roots of trees and other ___y plants. It is an organic material – a natural composite of cellulose fibers that are strong in tension and embedded in a matrix of lignin that resists compression. ___ is sometimes defined as only the secondary xylem in the stems of trees, In a living tree it performs a support function, enabling ___y plants to grow large or to stand up by themselves. It also conveys water and nutrients between the leaves, other growing tissues, and the roots. ___ may also refer to other plant materials with comparable properties, and to material engineered from ___, or ___ chips or fiber.","wiki"),("root","4","In vascular plants, the ___s are the organs of a plant that typically lie below the surface of the soil. ___s can also be aerial or aerating, that is, growing up above the ground or especially above water. Furthermore, a stem normally occurring below ground is not exceptional either . Therefore, the ___ is best defined as the non-leaf, non-nodes bearing parts of the plant's body. There are important internal structural differences between stems and ___s.","wiki"),("seed","4","A ___ is an embryonic plant enclosed in a protective outer covering. The formation of the ___ is part of the process of reproduction in ___ plants, the spermatophytes, including the gymnosperm and angiosperm plants.","wiki"),("self","4","___-pollination is when pollen from the same plant arrives at the stigma of a flower , or stamens that move to come into contact with the stigma. The term ___ing that is often used as a synonym, is not limited to ___-pollination, but also applies to other types of ___-fertilization.","wiki"),("corm","4","A ___, bulbo-tuber, or bulbotuber is a short, vertical, swollen underground plant stem that serves as a storage organ that some plants use to survive winter or other adverse conditions such as summer drought and heat .","wiki"),("twig","4","A ___ is a thin branch of a tree or bush.","wiki"),("lily","4","Lilium  is a genus of herbaceous flowering plants growing from bulbs, all with large prominent flowers. Lilies are a group of flowering plants which are important in culture and literature in much of the world. Most species are native to the temperate northern hemisphere, though their range extends into the northern subtropics. Many other plants have '___' in their common name but are not related to true lilies.","wiki"),("flax","4","___ , also known as common ___ or linseed, is a member of the genus Linum in the family Linaceae. It is a food and fiber crop cultivated in cooler regions of the world. Textiles made from ___ are known in the Western countries as linen, and traditionally used for bed sheets, underclothes, and table linen. Its oil is known as linseed oil. In addition to referring to the plant itself, the word '___' may refer to the unspun fibers of the ___ plant. The plant species is known only as a cultivated plant, The plants called '___' in New Zealand are, by contrast, members of the genus Phormium.","wiki"),("pith","4","___, or medulla, is a tissue in the stems of vascular plants. ___ is composed of soft, spongy parenchyma cells, which store and transport nutrients throughout the plant. In eudicotyledons, ___ is located in the center of the stem. In monocotyledons, it extends also into flowering stems and roots. The ___ is encircled by a ring of xylem; the xylem, in turn, is encircled by a ring of phloem.","wiki"),("tree","4","In botany, a ___ is a perennial plant with an elongated stem, or trunk, supporting branches and leaves in most species. In some usages, the definition of a ___ may be narrower, including only woody plants with secondary growth, plants that are usable as lumber or plants above a specified height. In wider definitions, the taller palms, ___ ferns, bananas, and bamboos are also ___s. ___s are not a taxonomic group but include a variety of plant species that have independently evolved a trunk and branches as a way to tower above other plants to compete for sunlight. ___s tend to be long-lived, some reaching several thousand years old.  ___s have been in existence for 370 million years. It is estimated that there are just over 3 trillion mature ___s in the world.","wiki"),("pine","4","See List of Pinus species for complete taxonomy to species level. See list of ___s by region for list of species by geographic distribution.","wiki"),("toys","4","A toy is an item that is used in play, especially one designed for such use. Playing with ___ can be an enjoyable means of training young children for life in society. Different materials like wood, clay, paper, and plastic are used to make ___. Many items are designed to serve as ___, but goods produced for other purposes can also be used. For instance, a small child may fold an ordinary piece of paper into an airplane shape and 'fly it'.Newer forms of ___ include interactive digital entertainment. Some ___ are produced primarily as collectors' items and are intended for display only.","wiki"),("tool","4","A ___ is an object used to extend the ability of an individual to modify features of the surrounding environment. Although many animals use simple ___s, only human beings, whose use of stone ___s dates back hundreds of millennia, have been observed using ___s to make other ___s.  The set of ___s required to perform different tasks that are part of the same activity is called gear or equipment.","wiki"),("reed","4","The cosmopolitan common ___ has the generally accepted botanical name Phragmites australis. .","wiki"),("hemp","4","___, or industrial ___, is a strain of the Cannabis sativa plant species that is grown specifically for the industrial uses of its derived products.","wiki"),("jute","4","___ is one of the most affordable natural fibers, and second only to cotton in the amount produced and variety of uses. ___ fibers are composed primarily of the plant materials cellulose and lignin. It falls into the bast fiber category  long. ___ is also called the golden fiber for its color and high cash value.","wiki"),("watt","4","The ___  it is defined as a derived unit of 1 joule per second, The ___ is named after James ___, an 18th-century Scottish inventor.","wiki"),("beef","4","___ is the culinary name for meat from cattle, particularly skeletal muscle. Humans have been eating ___ since prehistoric times.","wiki"),("pork","4","___ is eaten both freshly cooked and preserved. Curing extends the shelf life of the ___ products. Ham, smoked ___, gammon, bacon and sausage are examples of preserved ___. Charcuterie is the branch of cooking devoted to prepared meat products, many from ___.","wiki"),("eggs","4","Some ___ are laid by female animals of many different species, including birds, reptiles, amphibians, mammals, and fish, and have been eaten by humans for thousands of years. Bird and reptile ___ consist of a protective ___hell, albumen , contained within various thin membranes. The most commonly consumed ___ are chicken ___. Other poultry ___ including those of duck and quail also are eaten. Fish ___ are called roe and caviar.","wiki"),("tofu","4","___, also known as bean curd, is a food prepared by coagulating soy milk and then pressing the resulting curds into solid white blocks of varying softness; it can be silken, soft, firm, or extra firm. Beyond these broad categories, there are many varieties of ___. It has a subtle flavor, so it can be used in savory and sweet dishes. It is often seasoned or marinated to suit the dish and its flavors, and due to its spongy texture it absorbs flavors well.","wiki"),("iron","4","Human ___ metabolism is the set of chemical reactions that maintain human homeostasis of ___ at the systemic and cellular level.  ___ is both necessary to the body and potentially toxic. Controlling ___ levels in the body is a critically important part of many aspects of human health and disease. Hematologists have been especially interested in systemic ___ metabolism because ___ is essential for red blood cells, where most of the human body's ___ is contained. Understanding ___ metabolism is also important for understanding diseases of ___ overload, such as hereditary hemochromatosis, and ___ deficiency, such as ___ deficiency anemia.","wiki"),("soup","4","___ is a primarily liquid food, generally served warm or hot  than stews.","wiki"),("salt","4","___ is a mineral consisting primarily of sodium chloride  of solids per liter of sea water, a salinity of 3.5%.","wiki"),("zinc","4","___ is a chemical element with the symbol Zn and atomic number 30. ___ is a slightly brittle metal at room temperature and has a blue-silvery appearance when oxidation is removed. It is the first element in group 12 of the periodic table. In some respects, ___ is chemically similar to magnesium: both elements exhibit only one normal oxidation state .","wiki"),("soil","4","___ is a mixture of organic matter, minerals, gases, liquids, and organisms that together support life. Earth's body of ___, called the pedosphere, has four important functions:","wiki"),("noun","4","A ___ can co-occur with an article or an attributive adjective. Verbs and adjectives cannot. In the following, an asterisk  in front of an example means that this example is ungrammatical.","wiki"),("fats","4","Fat is an important foodstuff for many forms of life, and ___ serve both structural and metabolic functions.  They are a necessary part of the diet of most heterotrophs  and are the most energy dense, thus the most efficient form of energy storage.","wiki"),("rice","4","___ is the seed of the grass species Oryza glaberrima .","wiki"),("herb","4","In general use, ___s are plants with savory or aromatic properties that are used for flavoring and garnishing food, for medicinal purposes, or for fragrances; excluding vegetables and other plants consumed for macronutrients. Culinary use typically distinguishes ___s from spices. ___s generally refers to the leafy green or flowering parts of a plant , while spices are usually dried and produced from other parts of the plant, including seeds, bark, roots and fruits.","wiki"),("corn","4","Maize , is a cereal grain first domesticated by indigenous peoples in southern Mexico about 10,000 years ago.","wiki"),("meat","4","___ is animal flesh that is eaten as food. Humans have hunted and killed animals for ___ since prehistoric times. The advent of civilization allowed the domestication of animals such as chickens, sheep, rabbits, pigs and cattle. This eventually led to their use in ___ production on an industrial scale with the aid of slaughterhouses.","wiki"),("milk","4","___ is a nutrient-rich, white liquid food produced by the mammary glands of mammals. It is the primary source of nutrition for infant mammals  before they are able to digest other types of food.","wiki"),("bees","4","___ are flying insects closely related to wasps and ants, known for their role in pollination and, in the case of the best-known bee species, the western honey bee, for producing honey and ___wax. ___ are a monophyletic lineage within the superfamily Apoidea. They are presently considered a clade, called Anthophila. There are over 16,000 known species of ___ in seven recognized biological families.  They are found on every continent except for Antarctica, in every habitat on the planet that contains insect-pollinated flowering plants.","wiki"),("fork","4","In cutlery or kitchenware, a ___  is a utensil, now usually made of metal, whose 