gnaling and self-sustaining processes, from those that do not, either because such functions have ceased , or because they never had such functions and are classified as inanimate. Various forms of ___ exist, such as plants, animals, fungi, protists, archaea, and bacteria. Biology is the science concerned with the study of ___.","wiki"),("rain","4","The major cause of ___ production is moisture moving along three-dimensional zones of temperature and moisture contrasts known as weather fronts. If enough moisture and upward motion is present, precipitation falls from convective clouds  which can organize into narrow ___bands. In mountainous areas, heavy precipitation is possible where upslope flow is maximized within windward sides of the ter___ at elevation which forces moist air to condense and fall out as ___fall along the sides of mountains. On the leeward side of mountains, desert climates can exist due to the dry air caused by downslope flow which causes heating and drying of the air mass. The movement of the monsoon trough, or intertropical convergence zone, brings ___y seasons to savannah climes.","wiki"),("axil","4","The leaf-like organs of bryophytes . These can further develop into either vegetative or reproductive structures.","wiki"),("asia","4","___  constitute roughly 60% of the world's population.","wiki"),("deer","4","___ .","wiki"),("type","4","In biology, a ___ is a particular specimen , a ___ was a taxon rather than a specimen.","wiki"),("isis","4","___'s cult reached Italy and the Roman sphere of influence at some point in the second century BCE.","wiki"),("flag","4","The ___ of the United States of America, often referred to as the American ___ or U.S. ___, is the national ___ of the United States. It  consists of thirteen equal horizontal stripes of red  alternate with rows of five stars. The 50 stars on the ___ represent the 50 states of the United States of America, and the 13 stripes represent the thirteen British colonies that declared independence from the Kingdom of Great Britain, and became the first states in the U.S. and the Star-Spangled Banner.","wiki"),("flea","4","___, the common name for the order Siphonaptera, includes 2,500 species of small flightless insects that survive as external parasites of mammals and birds. ___s live by consuming blood, or hematophagy, from their hosts. Adult ___s grow to about 3 mm  long, are usually brown, and have bodies that are 'flattened' sideways or narrow, enabling them to move through their host's fur or feathers. They lack wings, but have strong claws preventing them from being dislodged, mouthparts adapted for piercing skin and sucking blood, and hind legs extremely well adapted for jumping. They are able to leap a distance of some 50 times their body length, a feat second only to jumps made by another group of insects, the superfamily of froghoppers. ___ larvae are worm-like with no limbs; they have chewing mouthparts and feed on organic debris left on their host's skin.","wiki"),("wasp","4","A ___ is any narrow-waisted insect of the order of ants, bees, ___s, and sawflies  that is neither a bee nor an ant; some of them can sting their insect prey. The ___-waisted insects are a complete natural group with a single ancestor; ___s are not such a group, as they do not include the bees and the ants.","wiki"),("tick","4","Almost all ___s belong to one of two major families, the Ixodidae or hard ___s, and the Argasidae or soft ___s. Adults have ovoid or pear-shaped bodies, which become engorged with blood when they feed, and eight legs. In addition to having a hard shield on their dorsal surfaces, hard ___s have a beak-like structure at the front containing the mouthparts, whereas soft ___s have their mouthparts on the underside of their bodies. Both families locate a potential host by odour or from changes in the environment.","wiki"),("frog","4","___s play a variety of roles in culture, appearing in folklore and fairy tales such as the Brothers Grimm story o