h cotton thread, although linen and silk threads are still available. Manufactured ___ may be made of synthetic fiber. A few modern artists make ___ with a fine copper or silver wire instead of thread.","wiki"),("rope","4","A ___ is a group of yarns, plies, fibers or strands that are twisted or braided together into a larger and stronger form. ___s have tensile strength and so can be used for dragging and lifting. ___ is thicker and stronger than similarly constructed cord, string, and twine.","wiki"),("yarn","4","___ is a long continuous length of interlocked fibres, suitable for use in the production of textiles, sewing, crocheting, knitting, weaving, embroidery, or ropemaking. Embroidery threads are ___s specifically designed for needlework.","wiki"),("coir","4","___  are in upholstery padding, sacking and horticulture. White ___, harvested from unripe coconuts, is used for making finer brushes, string, rope and fishing nets.  It has the advantage of not sinking, so can be used in long lengths on deep water without the added weight dragging down boats and buoys.","wiki"),("hair","4","___ is a protein filament that grows from follicles found in the dermis. ___ is one of the defining characteristics of mammals.The human body, apart from areas of glabrous skin, is covered in follicles which produce thick terminal and fine vellus ___. Most common interest in ___ is focused on ___ growth, ___ types, and ___ care, but ___ is also an important biomaterial primarily composed of protein, notably alpha-keratin.","wiki"),("silk","4","___ is a natural protein fiber, some forms of which can be woven into textiles. The protein fiber of ___ is composed mainly of fibroin and is produced by certain insect larvae to form cocoons. The best-known ___ is obtained from the cocoons of the larvae of the mulberry ___worm Bombyx mori reared in captivity . The shimmering appearance of ___ is due to the triangular prism-like structure of the ___ fibre, which allows ___ cloth to refract inco